SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"AI Governance Structures & Roles", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>AI governance</span> is the management system that decides whether, how, and under what controls AI is designed, built, acquired, deployed, and monitored. It fuses people, policy, and process with technical guardrails so that AI systems stay lawful, secure, reliable, and aligned to business objectives. Unlike traditional GRC, which leans on manual processes, static frameworks, and periodic assessments, AI GRC must contend with systems that <em>learn</em> from data and whose behavior can drift after release. The structural answer most organizations adopt is an <span class='keyterm'>AI Center of Excellence (CoE)</span> backed by formal policy, procedures, and clearly defined roles.</p><h3>The AI Center of Excellence</h3><p>An AI CoE is a cross-functional hub that blends AI engineering and data science with information security, privacy, legal, compliance, risk management, procurement, IT operations, and product management. The CoE defines standards, reviews projects, curates approved tools and platforms, writes and maintains the AI policy, publishes templates, advises on risk, and frequently leads investigations when AI incidents occur. Positioning varies along three models. A <strong>centralized</strong> model concentrates most development and all governance in one team, which accelerates standardization and suits smaller or heavily regulated organizations. A <strong>federated</strong> model embeds developers inside business units and uses the CoE as a standards-and-assurance function. A <strong>hybrid</strong> model centralizes platforms, policies, and reviews while letting business units build within predefined boundaries; it is the most common because it balances control against speed.</p><table><thead><tr><th>CoE model</th><th>Where build happens</th><th>Strengths</th><th>Best fit</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Centralized</td><td>One core team builds and governs</td><td>Fast standardization, tight control, simple audit trail</td><td>Smaller or heavily regulated organizations</td></tr><tr><td>Federated</td><td>Business-unit teams build; CoE sets standards</td><td>Domain speed, local ownership, scales across units</td><td>Large enterprises with mature units</td></tr><tr><td>Hybrid</td><td>Shared platform; units build within guardrails</td><td>Balances control and velocity; reusable platform</td><td>Most organizations</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Policy, Procedures, and Guardrails</h3><p>An <span class='keyterm'>AI policy</span> states what is allowed, what evidence audits require, and who may decide. It should be short enough to read in one sitting and define which actions demand formal sign-off, such as promoting a model to production, training on customer data, or enabling autonomous actions like automated emails or transactions. <span class='keyterm'>AI procedures</span> convert policy into predictable, auditable actions, specifying who does what, when, and with what evidence across the lifecycle. <span class='keyterm'>Technical guardrails</span> — model and prompt registries with versioning, least-privilege access, secrets management, data masking, logging, and prompt or response filtering — enforce the policy in daily operation and reduce shadow AI.</p><h3>Accountability and RACI</h3><p>Effective programs assign explicit decision rights using a RACI map (Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, Informed). The role that is <strong>Accountable</strong> is singular and senior; the others may be plural.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Role</th><th>Primary responsibility</th><th>Typical RACI</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Executive sponsor / board</td><td>Owns AI risk appetite and final escalation</td><td>Accountable</td></tr><tr><td>AI governance engineer</td><td>Codifies approval workflows, collects evidence</td><td>Responsible</td></tr><tr><td>AI risk analyst</td><td>Assesses use cases, recommends mitigations</td><td>Responsible</td></tr><tr><td>AI security architect</td><td>Protects data, models, prompts from threats</td><td>Responsible</td></tr><tr><td>Data scientist / ML engineer</td><td>Build and validate models</td><td>Consulted</td></tr><tr><td>AI auditor</td><td>Independent assurance, recreates decisions</td><td>Consulted</td></tr><tr><td>Legal / privacy / compliance</td><td>Regulatory alignment, DPIAs</td><td>Consulted</td></tr><tr><td>End-user business teams</td><td>Operate within approved boundaries</td><td>Informed</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Modern AI programs distribute work across many roles: the <strong>data engineer</strong> builds pipelines that acquire, clean, and label data; the <strong>data scientist</strong> defines the problem and baseline models; the <strong>ML engineer</strong> productionizes prototypes; the <strong>AI architect</strong> designs how components fit the enterprise; the <strong>platform engineer</strong> provides shared infrastructure; and the <strong>MLOps engineer</strong> automates the lifecycle, versioning, and drift monitoring. Layered on top, the <strong>AI security architect</strong>, <strong>AI governance engineer</strong>, <strong>AI risk analyst</strong>, and <strong>AI auditor</strong> add protection, accountability, and assurance.</p><h3>A governance walkthrough</h3><p>Consider how these structures behave for a single proposal — a marketing team wanting to launch a generative email assistant. The team submits an intake request; the CoE classifies it against the policy's risk definitions and finds it touches customer data, so it is rated medium risk and routed for a design review. The <strong>AI risk analyst</strong> assesses use, recommending a no-train contractual clause and human review of drafts. The <strong>AI security architect</strong> requires prompt and response filtering plus least-privilege access to the mailing system. The <strong>AI governance engineer</strong> codifies an approval gate so the model cannot reach production until a fairness and PII test passes and the support director — the <strong>Accountable</strong> party — signs off. After launch, the <strong>AI auditor</strong> samples logged decisions and confirms the approval matched policy. Each handoff produces a dated artifact, so the chain from business request to production decision is reconstructable. This is the practical payoff of explicit decision rights: no single engineer can quietly push an unreviewed model live, and when something goes wrong the organization can name exactly who approved what, when, and on what evidence — which is precisely what a regulator or a litigant will ask for.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>When a question asks <em>who is accountable</em>, there can be only one accountable party and it is the senior owner, not the builder. The phrase &quot;the model did it&quot; is a governance failure — accountability must always trace to a person.</div><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Note</div>An <span class='keyterm'>AI GRC maturity roadmap</span> typically moves in stages: publish a concise policy and inventory existing AI uses, then stand up a model registry and adopt an industry standard, then refine risk practices, automate evidence collection, and seek independent third-party validation for high-risk systems.</div>"}
);
SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"The NIST AI Risk Management Framework", body:"<p>The <span class='keyterm'>NIST AI Risk Management Framework (AI RMF 1.0)</span>, published in January 2023, is a voluntary, rights-preserving framework that has been widely adopted well beyond the United States because of its practicality. It organizes AI risk management into four functions — <strong>Govern, Map, Measure, and Manage</strong> — each with categories, subcategories, suggested actions, and references. The companion <em>AI RMF Playbook</em> supplies concrete tactics, and a 2024 <span class='keyterm'>Generative AI Profile (NIST AI 600-1)</span> tailors the framework to large language and foundation models. NIST frames trustworthy AI around seven characteristics: valid and reliable, safe, secure and resilient, accountable and transparent, explainable and interpretable, privacy-enhanced, and fair with harmful bias managed.</p><h3>Govern — the cross-cutting function</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Govern</span> is woven through the other three functions rather than executed once. It cultivates a risk-aware culture: policies and procedures, accountability structures, workforce diversity and competency, legal and regulatory alignment, and processes for third-party and supply-chain risk. Govern answers &quot;does the organization have the people, policies, and oversight to manage AI risk at all?&quot; Without it, Map, Measure, and Manage produce evidence that nobody owns or acts upon. Govern's categories are concrete: <strong>Govern 1</strong> covers legal and regulatory requirements and a documented risk-management process; <strong>Govern 2</strong> assigns accountability structures and trained, diverse teams; <strong>Govern 3</strong> embeds workforce diversity and inclusion in risk decisions; <strong>Govern 4</strong> builds a culture that surfaces and communicates risk; <strong>Govern 5</strong> establishes feedback channels with affected stakeholders; and <strong>Govern 6</strong> addresses third-party and supply-chain risk for acquired data and models. Mapping internal controls to these numbered subcategories is what lets an auditor trace a policy back to a recognized outcome.</p><h3>Map, Measure, and Manage</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Map</span> establishes context and frames risk: it documents the system's purpose, intended and prohibited uses, stakeholders, and the categorization of impacts on people, organizations, and society. It is where you decide whether a use case is even appropriate. <span class='keyterm'>Measure</span> applies quantitative and qualitative methods to analyze, assess, benchmark, and monitor the risks Map identified — accuracy, robustness, fairness metrics, security testing, drift indicators, and red-team results. <span class='keyterm'>Manage</span> allocates resources to treat the measured risks: prioritizing, responding to, recovering from, and communicating about incidents, and deciding to accept, mitigate, transfer, or avoid each risk. A worked example clarifies the flow: for a resume-screening model, <strong>Map</strong> records that the use influences hiring (a rights-impacting decision), names candidates and recruiters as stakeholders, and prohibits use for protected-class inference; <strong>Measure</strong> then benchmarks selection-rate parity and true-positive rates across demographic groups and red-teams the model for prompt-driven leakage; and <strong>Manage</strong> decides to mitigate a discovered disparity by removing a proxy feature, assigns the fix an owner and review date, and communicates the residual risk to the hiring leader. The same evidence Measure produced becomes the audit record Manage acts on.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Function</th><th>Core question</th><th>Representative outcomes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Govern</td><td>Do we have the culture and structures to manage AI risk?</td><td>Policies, roles, accountability, third-party processes, legal alignment</td></tr><tr><td>Map</td><td>What is the context and what could go wrong?</td><td>Use-case framing, stakeholder mapping, impact categorization</td></tr><tr><td>Measure</td><td>How big and how likely are the risks?</td><td>Metrics, benchmarks, testing, TEVV, monitoring instrumentation</td></tr><tr><td>Manage</td><td>What do we do about the risks?</td><td>Prioritization, treatment, response, recovery, communication</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>TEVV and the lifecycle</h3><p>NIST emphasizes <span class='keyterm'>Test, Evaluation, Verification, and Validation (TEVV)</span> applied continuously across the AI lifecycle rather than as a one-time gate. Because AI behavior depends on data that shifts, the framework treats measurement as ongoing instrumentation. The RMF is deliberately non-prescriptive about specific thresholds, which lets organizations of different sizes and sectors implement it proportionally while still mapping their controls back to recognizable functions during an audit. The framework also stresses that risk should be evaluated relative to a meaningful baseline — comparing AI outcomes against the human or legacy process being replaced — so that an organization neither overstates nor ignores the marginal risk an AI system introduces.</p><h3>Why the RMF travels well</h3><p>Although authored by a US agency, the AI RMF has been adopted internationally because it is voluntary, sector-agnostic, and outcome-oriented rather than control-prescriptive, which lets it sit comfortably alongside binding regimes such as the EU AI Act and certifiable standards such as ISO/IEC 42001. Crosswalks published by NIST and others map RMF subcategories to those instruments, so an organization can use one set of evidence to address several obligations. The framework's vocabulary — trustworthy characteristics, the four functions, and TEVV — has become a common language that lets product, legal, and engineering teams discuss AI risk without each inventing its own terms, which is itself a meaningful reduction in organizational friction.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Note</div>Map, Measure, and Manage are roughly sequential for a single use case, but Govern runs through all of them continuously. A common mistake is to treat Govern as &quot;step zero&quot; that ends once policy is written.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Match the verb to the function: <em>frame/contextualize</em> = Map, <em>analyze/benchmark/monitor</em> = Measure, <em>prioritize/respond/recover</em> = Manage, <em>oversee/culture/policy</em> = Govern. The Generative AI Profile (AI 600-1) is the artifact that extends the RMF to LLM-specific risks like confabulation and CBRN information.</div>"}
);
SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"ISO/IEC 42001 & AI Management Systems", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>ISO/IEC 42001:2023</span> is the world's first certifiable management-system standard for artificial intelligence. It specifies the requirements for establishing, implementing, maintaining, and continually improving an <span class='keyterm'>AI Management System (AIMS)</span>. Like ISO 27001 for information security or ISO 9001 for quality, it follows the common <strong>Annex SL High-Level Structure</strong>, which means clauses 4 through 10 mirror other management systems and integrate cleanly with an existing ISMS. Because it is certifiable, organizations can undergo third-party assessment to demonstrate responsible AI management — powerful evidence for vendor assurance, procurement, and regulatory alignment.</p><h3>The clause structure</h3><p>The core requirements live in clauses 4 to 10, and certification depends on conformance to all of them. The standard uses the Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle to drive continual improvement.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Clause</th><th>Title</th><th>What it requires</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>4</td><td>Context of the organization</td><td>Determine internal/external issues, interested parties, AIMS scope</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Leadership</td><td>Top-management commitment, AI policy, roles and responsibilities</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Planning</td><td>AI risk assessment, AI risk treatment, AI system impact assessment, objectives</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>Support</td><td>Resources, competence, awareness, communication, documented information</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>Operation</td><td>Operational planning and control of the AI lifecycle</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td>Performance evaluation</td><td>Monitoring, measurement, internal audit, management review</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>Improvement</td><td>Nonconformity, corrective action, continual improvement</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Annex A controls and the AI impact assessment</h3><p>ISO/IEC 42001 ships with <span class='keyterm'>Annex A</span>, a normative list of roughly 38 controls grouped into around nine objectives covering AI policies, internal organization, resources (data, tooling, compute, human), assessing AI system impacts, the AI system lifecycle, data for AI systems, information for interested parties, use of AI systems, and third-party relationships. <span class='keyterm'>Annex B</span> gives implementation guidance for those controls, and <span class='keyterm'>Annex C</span> catalogs potential AI-related organizational objectives and risk sources. A distinctive requirement is the <span class='keyterm'>AI system impact assessment (AISIA)</span>, which evaluates consequences for individuals, groups, and society — not merely the organization — making it broader than a traditional risk assessment.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Annex A objective area</th><th>Representative control intent</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>AI policies</td><td>Documented, approved, periodically reviewed AI policy</td></tr><tr><td>Internal organization</td><td>Defined AI roles, responsibilities, and reporting of concerns</td></tr><tr><td>Resources for AI</td><td>Govern data, tooling, compute, and human competencies</td></tr><tr><td>Assessing impacts</td><td>Conduct the AI system impact assessment (individuals and society)</td></tr><tr><td>AI system lifecycle</td><td>Responsible development, verification, deployment, and operation</td></tr><tr><td>Data for AI systems</td><td>Manage provenance, quality, and preparation of data</td></tr><tr><td>Information for interested parties</td><td>Provide documentation and transparency to users and regulators</td></tr><tr><td>Use of AI systems</td><td>Define responsible-use expectations and intended purpose</td></tr><tr><td>Third-party relationships</td><td>Allocate responsibilities across suppliers and customers</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The supporting standards family</h3><p>ISO/IEC 42001 does not stand alone. <span class='keyterm'>ISO/IEC 23894:2023</span> provides AI-specific risk-management guidance, aligning AI risk with the enterprise ISO 31000 approach. <span class='keyterm'>ISO/IEC 22989:2022</span> defines AI concepts and terminology so that words like &quot;model,&quot; &quot;training data,&quot; and &quot;bias&quot; mean the same thing across teams. <span class='keyterm'>ISO/IEC 5338:2023</span> details AI system lifecycle processes, including concept drift and model decay. Together these reduce friction between vendors and auditors and give organizations a shared, auditable vocabulary.</p><h3>Certification and the path to assurance</h3><p>Certification follows the familiar accredited-certification-body model. An organization first builds the AIMS, runs internal audits and a management review under clause 9, remediates nonconformities under clause 10, then engages an accredited body for a Stage 1 documentation review followed by a Stage 2 on-site assessment of the operating system. Surveillance audits maintain the certificate over a typical three-year cycle. Because the standard shares its Annex SL backbone with ISO 27001 and ISO 9001, an organization with an existing ISMS can extend rather than rebuild — reusing its risk methodology, document-control process, and internal-audit program — which materially lowers the cost of adoption. The chief advantage is portable assurance: instead of answering hundreds of bespoke vendor questionnaires, a certified provider points to an independent certificate, and buyers gain confidence that responsible-AI claims are backed by an audited process rather than marketing language. A practical sequencing example shows the effort involved: an organization with an existing ISO 27001 ISMS scopes the AIMS to its customer-facing generative features (clause 4), secures a signed AI policy and named owner from leadership (clause 5), runs an AI risk assessment and the AISIA and sets measurable objectives (clause 6), confirms competence and document control (clause 7), wires the lifecycle controls into operations (clause 8), completes an internal audit and management review (clause 9), and closes findings (clause 10) before the Stage 1 review even begins. Because Annex A is a reference set rather than a fixed mandate, the organization produces a <span class='keyterm'>Statement of Applicability</span> justifying which controls apply and why any are excluded — exactly mirroring the ISO 27001 model its team already knows, which is what keeps the marginal cost of certification low.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A SaaS vendor adding generative features wants to shorten enterprise procurement cycles. Pursuing ISO/IEC 42001 certification lets it hand buyers an independent attestation of responsible AI management, reducing the buyer's need to run duplicate assessments — the certification becomes a sales accelerator, not just a compliance cost.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Remember the split: <strong>ISO/IEC 42001 = certifiable management system (the AIMS, clauses 4-10, Annex A controls)</strong>; <strong>ISO/IEC 23894 = risk-management guidance (not certifiable)</strong>; <strong>NIST AI RMF = voluntary US framework (Govern/Map/Measure/Manage)</strong>. If a question stresses third-party certification, the answer is 42001.</div>"}
);
SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Responsible & Trustworthy AI Principles", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Responsible AI</span> converts broad values into specific design and control expectations. Different organizations and frameworks phrase the principles differently — the OECD AI Principles, NIST trustworthy characteristics, and corporate codes overlap heavily — but the underlying concepts are stable. They matter because AI is a <span class='keyterm'>socio-technical system</span>: harm can originate not only in data and models but in the people, processes, and environments around them.</p><h3>The core principles</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Fairness</span> means outcomes should not disadvantage individuals based on protected or irrelevant characteristics; it demands examining training data for historical imbalances, measuring results across groups, and setting clear rules for acceptable disparity. <span class='keyterm'>Accountability</span> defines who is responsible for decisions and the systems behind them, at both organizational and individual levels, so that &quot;the model did it&quot; is never a valid excuse. <span class='keyterm'>Transparency and explainability</span> govern how well stakeholders can understand a system's reasoning; the appropriate depth scales with risk, so a medical diagnosis assistant owes far more explanation than a movie recommender. <span class='keyterm'>Privacy and data governance</span> require collecting and using data lawfully, minimally, and securely — managing consent, retention limits, de-identification, and filtering of prompts and outputs.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Principle</th><th>What it requires in practice</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Fairness</td><td>Bias audits, demographic parity / equal-opportunity metrics, disparity thresholds</td></tr><tr><td>Accountability</td><td>Named owners, decision logs, sign-off gates</td></tr><tr><td>Transparency / explainability</td><td>Model cards, decision logs, feature-importance summaries</td></tr><tr><td>Privacy / data governance</td><td>Consent, minimization, retention limits, redaction</td></tr><tr><td>Safety / security</td><td>Adversarial testing, poisoning defenses, prompt-injection controls</td></tr><tr><td>Human oversight</td><td>Human-in-the-loop / human-on-the-loop intervention</td></tr><tr><td>Sustainability</td><td>Track energy and hardware cost; prefer right-sized models</td></tr><tr><td>Inclusiveness / consistency</td><td>Accessible, representative, stable across demographics</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Human oversight models</h3><p>Two oversight patterns recur. <span class='keyterm'>Human-in-the-loop</span> means the AI proposes but a person makes the final decision — appropriate for high-stakes determinations such as medical dosing or creditworthiness. <span class='keyterm'>Human-on-the-loop</span> means the AI decides routine cases while a person monitors and can override. The choice depends on risk and system maturity; high-stakes decisions warrant human review or strict validation before any automatic action.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Oversight pattern</th><th>Who decides</th><th>Use when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Human-in-command</td><td>AI advisory only; human sets and bounds the system</td><td>Strategic or irreversible high-impact contexts</td></tr><tr><td>Human-in-the-loop</td><td>AI proposes, person approves every action</td><td>Medical dosing, credit denial, hiring rejection</td></tr><tr><td>Human-on-the-loop</td><td>AI acts on routine cases, person monitors and overrides</td><td>High-volume, lower-stakes triage</td></tr></tbody></table><p>A worked selection: an AI fraud-triage tool processing thousands of cases daily cannot use human-in-the-loop without negating its value, so the team chooses human-on-the-loop — the model auto-clears low-risk cases while an analyst monitors a dashboard and can override — but routes any case that would freeze an account to mandatory human approval, because freezing funds is a high-impact, hard-to-reverse action. The oversight model is thus chosen per action class, not per system.</p><h3>Sustainability, consistency, and inclusiveness</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Sustainability and social impact</span> ask how resources are used and what broader effects follow; responsible programs track the energy and hardware cost of training and inference and prefer smaller fine-tuned models over one giant general model when feasible. <span class='keyterm'>Consistency</span> ensures stable, equitable results across demographics and deployment scenarios and is supported by bias audits using fairness metrics like demographic parity and equal opportunity, plus adversarial testing. Closely related, <span class='keyterm'>inclusiveness</span> means designing and deploying systems that serve diverse populations equitably — accessible and representative across abilities and backgrounds.</p><h3>Validity, reliability, and robustness</h3><p>Underpinning every other principle is <span class='keyterm'>validity and reliability</span>: a system that does not actually work as claimed cannot be fair, safe, or trustworthy. NIST treats this as the foundational characteristic, encompassing accuracy on representative data, <span class='keyterm'>robustness</span> under unusual or adversarial inputs, and <span class='keyterm'>resilience</span> when conditions degrade. <span class='keyterm'>Safety and security</span> aim to prevent harm from misuse or attack — guarding against adversarial input manipulation, training-data poisoning, and prompt injection against large language models, while also covering misuse scenarios such as coaxing a code-generation model into writing harmful scripts. These technical characteristics must be balanced against one another; pushing accuracy too hard can reduce interpretability, and maximizing one fairness metric can worsen another, so responsible programs document the trade-offs they accepted and why. The OECD AI Principles and NIST's trustworthy characteristics map closely onto one another, which is why an organization can adopt one vocabulary internally and still satisfy partners who use the other: OECD's &quot;robustness, security and safety&quot; aligns with NIST's &quot;safe&quot; and &quot;secure and resilient,&quot; OECD's &quot;transparency and explainability&quot; with NIST's pairing of the same names, and OECD's &quot;accountability&quot; with NIST's &quot;accountable and transparent.&quot; Treating the principles as a checklist applied at design, test, and monitoring time — rather than a one-time ethics statement — is what converts them from aspiration into auditable control, and it is the failure to operationalize them, not the absence of the words, that regulators and customers penalize.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Note</div>Principles only become real through practice: define decision rights, document each system with a <span class='keyterm'>model card</span> (purpose, data sources, training period, limitations, intended users, prohibited uses), test before release (accuracy, fairness, stress, red-team), monitor after release, and prepare AI-specific incident playbooks.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Don't confuse <em>transparency</em> (disclosing that AI is used and how it works) with <em>explainability</em> (justifying a specific output). A chatbot disclosure label is transparency; a feature-importance explanation of a denied loan is explainability.</div>"}
);
SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"AI Risk Categories & Taxonomy", body:"<p>AI risk can be <strong>technical</strong> — a model producing incorrect results — or <strong>non-technical</strong> — reputational damage when a feature misbehaves. A useful mental model attributes risk across three lines: the <span class='keyterm'>business context</span> (what decision or workflow the AI influences and the impact of a poor recommendation), the <span class='keyterm'>data and model behavior</span> (how the system learns patterns and how those patterns become unreliable or skewed), and <span class='keyterm'>operations and oversight</span> (deployment, monitoring, incident handling, and accountability). Because AI is socio-technical, governance must look beyond the algorithm.</p><h3>Major risk categories</h3><p>While AI shares many risks with traditional software, some are unique because AI learns patterns from data rather than only following pre-written rules. The principal categories are summarized below.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Category</th><th>Example</th><th>Representative mitigation</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Bias / unfair outcomes</td><td>Loan model rejects qualified applicants from one region</td><td>Fairness criteria, demographic evaluation, data documentation</td></tr><tr><td>Privacy / data leakage</td><td>PII surfaces in outputs; prompts written to logs</td><td>Minimization, redaction, retention limits, access controls</td></tr><tr><td>Security threats</td><td>Poisoning, prompt injection, model inversion, adversarial inputs</td><td>Integrity checks, pipeline isolation, content filtering</td></tr><tr><td>Accuracy / drift</td><td>Phishing classifier fails on new generative tactics</td><td>Representative test sets, drift monitoring, retraining/rollback</td></tr><tr><td>Reputational harm</td><td>Assistant confidently gives wrong financial advice</td><td>Response boundaries, human escalation, incident playbooks</td></tr><tr><td>IP / provenance</td><td>Generative output resembles a living artist's portfolio</td><td>Licensing reviews, watermarking, signing, content review</td></tr><tr><td>Autonomy / real-world action</td><td>Support agent manipulated into issuing unauthorized refunds</td><td>Least-privilege scope, rate limits, reversible actions, human validation</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Risks unique to AI</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Distribution shift and model drift</span> occur when the world changes and production data no longer matches training data — a demand forecast trained before a new competitor enters degrades quickly. <span class='keyterm'>Hallucinations</span> arise when a model generates plausible but incorrect statements, mitigated by source grounding, retrieval-augmented generation that cites documents, and output verification. <span class='keyterm'>Data poisoning</span> manipulates training data to plant attacker-chosen behavior; <span class='keyterm'>model inversion</span> and <span class='keyterm'>membership inference</span> reconstruct or detect training records, creating privacy risk; and <span class='keyterm'>adversarial samples</span> alter inputs to look normal to humans while forcing misclassification.</p><h3>Over-trust and under-trust</h3><p>A subtle operational risk is human calibration. Users frequently <strong>over-trust</strong> AI because outputs are convincing, or <strong>under-trust</strong> it from lack of awareness. Both are addressed through training, interfaces that display uncertainty or supporting evidence, and procedural safeguards that mandate secondary checks for high-impact actions.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Likelihood \ Impact</th><th>Low impact</th><th>High impact</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>High likelihood</td><td>Tolerate &amp; monitor (chatbot gives unhelpful answer)</td><td>Mitigate now (frequent PII leakage in logs)</td></tr><tr><td>Low likelihood</td><td>Accept (rare formatting glitch)</td><td>Hard control / human gate (irreversible high-value transaction)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Mapping severity and likelihood</h3><p>Categorizing a risk is only the first step; governance must also rate each risk by <strong>likelihood</strong> and <strong>impact</strong> to prioritize treatment, exactly as in enterprise risk management. A low-likelihood, catastrophic-impact risk (an autonomous agent making an irreversible high-value transaction) may warrant a hard human-approval gate, while a high-likelihood, low-impact risk (a chatbot occasionally giving an unhelpful answer) may be tolerated and merely monitored. Each risk is then assigned a treatment decision — <span class='keyterm'>accept, mitigate, transfer, or avoid</span> — with a named owner and a review date. This discipline keeps the taxonomy from becoming a static list and turns it into a living register that drives where scarce engineering and oversight effort actually goes. It also produces the documented rationale that auditors and regulators expect to see behind every deployment decision.</p><h3>Technical versus non-technical risk</h3><p>A complete taxonomy spans both halves of the socio-technical system. <strong>Technical</strong> risks live in the data and model: drift, hallucination, poisoning, inversion, membership inference, and adversarial examples are all properties of how the system computes. <strong>Non-technical</strong> risks live in people and process: reputational harm when an assistant gives confident bad advice, intellectual-property exposure when generated output resembles a living artist's work, regulatory penalty when a high-risk use ships without an impact assessment, and the human-calibration failures of over- and under-trust. The two interact — a technical hallucination becomes a reputational and possibly legal event once it reaches a customer — which is why governance refuses to treat AI risk as &quot;an engineering problem.&quot; A useful discipline is to walk each candidate risk down all three lines (business context, data and model behavior, operations and oversight) and confirm a named control exists on each line before deployment; a model can be technically excellent yet fail because no one owns its monitoring or because its business context was never bounded. Mapping the register against a consolidated taxonomy such as the MIT AI Risk Repository then guards against the blind spot of a category no one on the team happened to think of.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A support agent empowered to process refunds is steered by a crafted prompt into issuing unauthorized credits. The fix is layered: minimal action scope, granular approvals, rate limits, reversible changes, human validation for high-impact actions, and treating the model as an untrusted client subject to the same authentication, authorization, and input validation as any external user.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Group risks by the line they live on. If a question describes <em>who is accountable</em> or <em>monitoring</em>, that is the operations/oversight line; if it describes <em>skewed training data</em>, that is the data/model line; if it describes <em>business impact of a bad recommendation</em>, that is the business-context line.</div>"}
);
SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"The MIT AI Risk Repository & Risk Classification", body:"<p>As the AI risk literature exploded, researchers found that no two frameworks named or organized risks the same way, making it hard to know whether a risk register was complete. The <span class='keyterm'>MIT AI Risk Repository</span>, released in 2024 by the MIT FutureTech group and collaborators, answers this by aggregating <strong>over 1,600 risks</strong> extracted from 65+ existing frameworks and taxonomies into a single, living, openly accessible database. It is designed as a common reference that auditors, policymakers, and risk teams can map their own controls against, reducing the chance of blind spots.</p><h3>Two complementary taxonomies</h3><p>The Repository classifies every risk along two axes. The <span class='keyterm'>Causal Taxonomy</span> describes <em>how, when, and why</em> a risk arises, using three dimensions: <strong>entity</strong> (human, AI, or other), <strong>intent</strong> (intentional, unintentional, or other), and <strong>timing</strong> (pre-deployment, post-deployment, or other). The <span class='keyterm'>Domain Taxonomy</span> describes <em>what</em> the risk concerns, sorting risks into <strong>7 domains</strong> further divided into <strong>24 subdomains</strong>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Domain</th><th>Example concern</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Discrimination &amp; toxicity</td><td>Unfair bias, exposure to toxic content</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Privacy &amp; security</td><td>Data leakage, AI system vulnerabilities</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Misinformation</td><td>False or misleading information, erosion of consensus</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Malicious actors &amp; misuse</td><td>Disinformation, cyberattacks, weapons development</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Human-computer interaction</td><td>Overreliance, loss of human agency</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Socioeconomic &amp; environmental</td><td>Inequality, job loss, energy and environmental cost</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>AI system safety, failures &amp; limitations</td><td>Misaligned goals, lack of capability or robustness</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Why the causal dimensions matter</h3><p>The Causal Taxonomy's distinctions are not academic. <span class='keyterm'>Intent</span> separates an attacker poisoning data (intentional, human entity) from a developer accidentally introducing a biased label (unintentional). <span class='keyterm'>Timing</span> separates risks baked in <strong>pre-deployment</strong> — flawed training data, poor objective specification — from those that emerge <strong>post-deployment</strong>, such as drift, misuse, or over-reliance. Knowing the timing tells you whether a control belongs in design and testing or in monitoring and incident response. Worked classification: a chatbot that confidently fabricates a refund policy is, on the Causal Taxonomy, an <em>AI</em> entity, <em>unintentional</em> intent, and <em>post-deployment</em> timing — which immediately points the team toward output grounding and monitoring rather than a training-time fix; by contrast, a poisoned open-weight dataset is a <em>human</em> entity, <em>intentional</em>, and <em>pre-deployment</em>, directing effort to supplier vetting and integrity checks. On the Domain Taxonomy the first case lands in domain 3 (misinformation) and the second in domain 2 (privacy &amp; security), so a single incident gets a coordinate on both axes. A striking finding from the Repository is that risks are not evenly distributed: a large share of documented risks are post-deployment and unintentional, which argues for heavy investment in monitoring rather than assuming all risk can be designed out before launch.</p><h3>Using the Repository in practice</h3><p>A risk team can take the 24 subdomains as a checklist, confirm each is addressed by at least one control, and use the Causal Taxonomy to verify coverage across both pre- and post-deployment timing. Because it consolidates dozens of frameworks, mapping to the Repository also helps demonstrate to auditors and regulators that a program's risk identification is comprehensive rather than ad hoc.</p><h3>Living catalog versus static framework</h3><p>A key design choice is that the Repository is a <span class='keyterm'>living database</span>, periodically updated as new frameworks and risks are published, rather than a fixed standard frozen at a point in time. This suits a field where novel risks — agentic misuse, model collapse from training on synthetic data, emergent capabilities — appear faster than formal standards can be revised. Teams can therefore re-baseline their risk coverage against the latest version rather than against a document that may be years out of date. The Repository pairs naturally with process frameworks: NIST's <strong>Map</strong> function or ISO 42001's impact assessment supply the <em>method</em> for identifying risks, while the Repository supplies a vetted <em>checklist</em> of what those risks might be, so an organization is far less likely to miss a category simply because no one on the team had thought of it. The scale of the consolidation is itself the value: by extracting over 1,600 risks from more than 65 source frameworks and reconciling them into seven domains and twenty-four subdomains, the Repository turns a fragmented literature — where one framework's &quot;misuse&quot; is another's &quot;malicious actors&quot; and a third's &quot;dual-use&quot; — into a single vocabulary. A risk team that has historically tracked, say, twelve risk types can overlay them on the twenty-four subdomains and immediately see which dozen subdomains it has never considered, converting an implicit gap into an explicit, assignable list of coverage decisions.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Note</div>Remember the headline numbers: <strong>1,600+ risks, 7 domains, 24 subdomains, 2 taxonomies (Causal and Domain)</strong>. The Causal Taxonomy uses three dimensions — entity, intent, timing.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>If a scenario asks how to ensure a risk register is <em>complete</em> or <em>comprehensive</em>, mapping it against a consolidated taxonomy like the MIT AI Risk Repository is the strong answer. Don't confuse the Repository (a research catalog of risks) with the NIST AI RMF (a process framework) — they complement each other.</div>"}
);
SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Bias, Fairness & Explainability Risks", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Bias</span> in AI is a systematic error that yields unfair or skewed outcomes for particular individuals or groups. Because models learn from data, bias can enter from many directions, and a high-accuracy model can still be deeply unfair to a subgroup. Governance treats fairness as something to be measured and managed, not assumed.</p><h3>Sources of bias</h3><p>Bias arises from training data that reflects historical inequities, from labeling practices that embed subjective human judgment, and from the deployment context itself. A loan-approval model trained mostly on applicants from one region may underperform for similar applicants elsewhere; a fraud model trained chiefly on weekday transactions may flag legitimate weekend behavior. Sampling and representation gaps, proxy variables that stand in for protected attributes, and feedback loops where a model's own outputs shape future training data all compound the problem.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Bias type</th><th>Origin</th><th>Mitigation</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Historical / societal</td><td>Past inequities encoded in data</td><td>Data profiling, reweighting, synthetic data for gaps</td></tr><tr><td>Representation / sampling</td><td>Under-sampled groups or scenarios</td><td>Balanced collection, evaluate on real-world distribution</td></tr><tr><td>Measurement / label</td><td>Subjective or inconsistent labeling</td><td>Label guidelines, inter-rater checks, documentation</td></tr><tr><td>Proxy</td><td>Features correlated with protected traits</td><td>Feature review, disparate-impact testing</td></tr><tr><td>Aggregation / deployment</td><td>One model applied across distinct groups</td><td>Subgroup evaluation, context-specific thresholds</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Measuring fairness</h3><p>Fairness must be operationalized through metrics. <span class='keyterm'>Demographic parity</span> requires that positive-outcome rates be similar across groups. <span class='keyterm'>Equal opportunity</span> requires similar true-positive rates across groups. <span class='keyterm'>Equalized odds</span> additionally constrains false-positive rates. These metrics can conflict — it is mathematically impossible to satisfy all fairness definitions simultaneously when base rates differ — so organizations must choose context-appropriate criteria, set acceptable disparity thresholds, and define an escalation path when thresholds are breached. Bias audits and <span class='keyterm'>adversarial testing</span> help surface inconsistencies in treatment of individuals protected by anti-discrimination law (race, ethnicity, gender, age, sexual orientation, disability, religion).</p><table><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Equalizes</th><th>Watch-out</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Demographic parity</td><td>Positive-outcome (selection) rates</td><td>Can force unequal treatment when base rates truly differ</td></tr><tr><td>Equal opportunity</td><td>True-positive rates</td><td>Ignores false-positive disparities</td></tr><tr><td>Equalized odds</td><td>True- and false-positive rates</td><td>Hardest to satisfy; may cut accuracy</td></tr><tr><td>Predictive parity</td><td>Precision (positive predictive value)</td><td>Conflicts with equalized odds under unequal base rates</td></tr></tbody></table><p>The conflict is not hypothetical. In a recidivism-style example where two groups have different underlying base rates, a model tuned to equal predictive parity will show unequal false-positive rates, and forcing equalized odds will break predictive parity — the formal impossibility result. A team therefore picks the metric that matches the harm it most wants to prevent (false denials of opportunity favor equal opportunity; unequal error burden favors equalized odds), sets a disparity threshold, and documents the choice and rationale in the model card so it survives audit.</p><h3>Model opacity and explainability</h3><p>Complex models — deep neural networks and foundation models — can be highly accurate yet difficult to interpret, which makes subtle discrimination or unintended logic hard to detect. Explainability techniques such as <span class='keyterm'>feature-importance analysis</span>, surrogate methods like <span class='keyterm'>SHAP</span> and <span class='keyterm'>LIME</span>, and thorough model documentation improve visibility. In regulated environments, organizations may deliberately choose simpler, inherently interpretable models when they deliver comparable performance, accepting a small accuracy trade-off for the ability to explain and defend each decision.</p><h3>Global versus local explanations</h3><p>It helps to distinguish <span class='keyterm'>global explainability</span> — understanding how a model behaves overall, which features drive its predictions across the population — from <span class='keyterm'>local explainability</span>, which explains a single output, such as why one specific applicant was denied. Regulatory regimes frequently demand the local form: a lending adverse-action notice or a GDPR Article 22 contestation requires a per-decision rationale, not a general description of the model. SHAP and LIME are local techniques; feature-importance and partial-dependence analyses lean global. Choosing the right explanation type for the obligation at hand is itself a governance decision, and documenting it in the model card prevents the common failure of producing technically impressive but legally useless explanations. Where genuine explainability is infeasible, compensating controls — tighter human oversight, narrower deployment scope, or a simpler model — become the responsible fallback. It is worth stressing that SHAP and LIME approximate a complex model's local behavior rather than revealing its true internal logic, so a plausible-looking explanation can itself mislead; mature programs validate that explanations are faithful (small input changes move the explanation sensibly) before relying on them in adverse-action notices or regulatory contestation, and they record that validation in the model card alongside the chosen fairness metric and threshold.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>An AI hiring tool shows higher rejection rates for one demographic group. The team runs a bias audit using demographic parity and equal-opportunity metrics, traces the disparity to a proxy feature correlated with a protected attribute, removes the feature, retrains, and re-tests — then documents the threshold and escalation path so the disparity is caught automatically next time.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Know the fairness-metric distinctions: <strong>demographic parity</strong> equalizes selection rates; <strong>equal opportunity</strong> equalizes true-positive rates; <strong>equalized odds</strong> equalizes both true- and false-positive rates. Expect a question noting that you generally cannot satisfy all fairness definitions at once.</div>"}
);
SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Third-Party & AI Supply-Chain Risk", body:"<p>Few organizations build AI entirely in-house. They rely on <span class='keyterm'>foundation models</span> from external providers, open weights from community hubs, third-party datasets, annotation vendors, and a stack of MLOps tooling. Each dependency imports risk that the consuming organization cannot fully see, so governance must treat AI suppliers as regulated parties subject to assessment, contractual controls, and ongoing validation.</p><h3>Where supply-chain risk enters</h3><p>The clearest risks are <span class='keyterm'>versioning and provenance</span>: a provider may update a model or dataset without notice, silently changing behavior an application depends on. Foundation models are opaque about their training data, which raises intellectual-property and privacy exposure. Open weights and community datasets may be poisoned or carry unclear licenses. Tooling and libraries add a conventional software supply-chain attack surface. Strong governance responds with supplier assessments, the use of <span class='keyterm'>signed artifacts</span>, internal validation checks before any major upgrade, and contractual commitments on data use, indemnification, and retention of prompts and outputs.</p><p>A worked onboarding makes this concrete. Before adopting a foundation-model API, the consuming team collects the provider's SOC 2 Type II report and recent penetration-test summary, confirms a contractual no-train clause and data-residency commitment, pins an explicit model version rather than a floating &quot;latest&quot; alias, and runs the model through an internal evaluation gate measuring accuracy, refusal behavior, and prompt-injection resilience on its own representative prompts. The version, the evaluation results, and the contract terms are recorded against the model-registry entry. When the provider later announces a new version, the same evaluation gate re-runs and the upgrade is blocked until it passes — so a silent behavior change cannot reach production unnoticed.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Dependency</th><th>Key risk</th><th>Control</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Foundation / public model</td><td>Opaque training data, silent version change, data used to train provider</td><td>Contractual no-train clause, version pinning, evaluation gates</td></tr><tr><td>Open weights</td><td>Poisoning, unclear license, no support</td><td>Signed/hashed artifacts, license review, internal red-team</td></tr><tr><td>Third-party / community data</td><td>Provenance gaps, embedded PII, bias</td><td>Data lineage review, sampling, licensing checks</td></tr><tr><td>Annotation vendor</td><td>Inconsistent or biased labels</td><td>Label guidelines, inter-rater audits, attestations</td></tr><tr><td>MLOps tooling / libraries</td><td>Conventional software supply-chain compromise</td><td>SBOM, dependency scanning, signing</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Private versus public models</h3><p>A central policy decision is <span class='keyterm'>public</span> versus <span class='keyterm'>private models</span>. Public models are multi-tenant cloud services — fast and capable, but raising questions about where prompts and outputs are stored, whether data trains the provider's models, and how jurisdictional rules apply. Private models run in a logically isolated environment (dedicated tenant, virtual private cloud, or on-premises), giving control over data residency, keys, logging, and tuning at higher engineering cost. Sound policy does not ban public models; it sets decision criteria, reserving private deployments with customer-managed keys and contractual no-train guarantees for high-risk data such as health or financial records.</p><h3>Shadow AI</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Shadow AI</span> — unsanctioned tools employees adopt on their own, such as free public chatbots or browser extensions — is one of the most pervasive supply-chain risks because it bypasses every control. The remedy is twofold: discourage unsafe use <em>and</em> provide attractive sanctioned alternatives, for example a searchable catalog of pre-approved assistants with single sign-on, so employees prefer the approved path. Sanctioned AI is vetted, configured for security and privacy, and supported by IT and legal; the policy's job is to make the safe choice the easy choice.</p><h3>Inherited and concentration risk</h3><p>Two structural features deserve special attention. <span class='keyterm'>Inherited risk</span> means a flaw in an upstream foundation model — a bias, a security weakness, a problematic training-data source — propagates into every downstream application built on it, so a single provider's problem can become an industry-wide exposure. <span class='keyterm'>Concentration risk</span> arises because a handful of providers supply most foundation models; an outage, price change, deprecation, or policy shift at one of them can simultaneously disrupt thousands of dependent organizations. Sound governance treats these like any critical-vendor dependency: it maintains an exit and portability plan, avoids hard-coding to a single provider's quirks where feasible, and tracks deprecation notices so a model retired by the vendor does not silently break a production workflow. Contracts should pin acceptable model versions, require advance notice of material changes, and define support and security-patch commitments, because the consuming organization remains accountable to its own customers and regulators regardless of which supplier introduced the defect. The EU AI Act reinforces this directly: a deployer that substantially modifies a high-risk system or puts its own brand on it can legally become the provider and inherit the heavier provider obligations, so supply-chain governance is not merely prudent but a route by which legal accountability transfers.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Note</div>Independent assurance matters here: enterprise buyers commonly require a current <span class='keyterm'>SOC 2 Type II</span> report, a recent penetration test, and a documented privacy assessment before integrating an external AI service, and may require evidence of a model-risk-management program in finance and healthcare.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>The defining trait of <strong>shadow AI</strong> is that it is <em>unsanctioned</em> — adopted without approval, bypassing governance. The defining mitigation is offering a sanctioned, easy-to-use alternative, not merely banning tools. For sensitive data, the expected answer favors <em>private</em> models with customer-managed keys and no-train guarantees.</div>"}
);
SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"The EU AI Act", body:"<p>The <span class='keyterm'>EU AI Act</span> (Regulation (EU) 2024/1689) is the world's first comprehensive, horizontal AI law, applying across all EU Member States. It entered into force on <strong>1 August 2024</strong>, with most obligations applying from <strong>2 August 2026</strong> and some on other dates — prohibited practices applied from February 2025, and general-purpose AI (GPAI) obligations from August 2025. Crucially, it has <span class='keyterm'>extraterritorial reach</span>: it binds providers and deployers outside the EU whenever their AI system's output is used within the Union, so it affects organizations worldwide.</p><h3>The four risk tiers</h3><p>The Act is fundamentally <strong>risk-based</strong>, sorting AI into four tiers with escalating obligations. The principle is proportionality: the more a system can affect health, safety, or fundamental rights, the heavier the compliance burden, while genuinely trivial uses are left essentially unregulated to avoid stifling innovation.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tier</th><th>Examples</th><th>Obligation</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Unacceptable risk</td><td>Government social scoring, manipulative subliminal techniques, untargeted facial-image scraping, most real-time biometric identification in public</td><td>Prohibited (Article 5)</td></tr><tr><td>High risk</td><td>AI in critical infrastructure, employment, credit/insurance, education, law enforcement, medical devices (Annex III)</td><td>Conformity assessment, risk management, data governance, logging, human oversight, post-market monitoring</td></tr><tr><td>Limited risk</td><td>Chatbots, emotion recognition, deepfakes / synthetic media</td><td>Transparency: disclose AI interaction, label synthetic content</td></tr><tr><td>Minimal risk</td><td>Spam filters, AI in video games</td><td>No mandatory obligations (voluntary codes encouraged)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>High-risk obligations</h3><p>High-risk systems carry the heaviest load. Providers must implement a continuous <span class='keyterm'>risk management system</span>, satisfy <span class='keyterm'>data governance</span> requirements for training, validation, and test data, maintain detailed <span class='keyterm'>technical documentation</span> and automatic event <span class='keyterm'>logging</span>, ensure transparency to deployers, design for <span class='keyterm'>human oversight</span>, and achieve appropriate accuracy, robustness, and cybersecurity. They must undergo a <span class='keyterm'>conformity assessment</span>, affix CE marking, and register in an EU database before placing the system on the market, then perform <span class='keyterm'>post-market monitoring</span>. Deployers also carry duties, including using systems per instructions and conducting a <span class='keyterm'>fundamental rights impact assessment (FRIA)</span> in certain public-interest contexts. <span class='keyterm'>Annex III</span> enumerates the high-risk categories explicitly: biometric identification, critical infrastructure management, education and vocational training, employment and worker management, access to essential private and public services (including credit scoring), law enforcement, migration and border control, and administration of justice — so classifying a system starts by checking it against this list and against the Article 5 prohibitions before any lighter tier is considered.</p><h3>General-purpose AI and penalties</h3><p>The Act adds a distinct regime for <span class='keyterm'>general-purpose AI (GPAI) models</span>, with baseline transparency and copyright duties for all and stricter obligations for models posing <span class='keyterm'>systemic risk</span> (above a compute threshold of 10^25 FLOPs), such as model evaluations, adversarial testing, and incident reporting. Penalties are steep and tiered: up to <strong>EUR 35 million or 7% of global annual turnover</strong> for prohibited-practice violations, up to EUR 15 million or 3% for most other breaches, and up to EUR 7.5 million or 1% for supplying incorrect information. In each case the regulation specifies &quot;whichever is higher,&quot; so for large multinationals the percentage of global turnover, not the fixed sum, is the binding ceiling — a design choice that makes the Act bite even on the largest providers.</p><h3>Roles and the compliance timeline</h3><p>The Act assigns duties by role. A <span class='keyterm'>provider</span> develops or places a system on the market and bears the bulk of high-risk obligations; a <span class='keyterm'>deployer</span> uses a system under its own authority and must follow instructions, ensure human oversight, and in some cases run a FRIA; <span class='keyterm'>importers</span> and <span class='keyterm'>distributors</span> carry verification duties. A pivotal rule is that a deployer who substantially modifies a high-risk system, or puts its own name on it, can legally become a provider and inherit those heavier obligations. The phased timeline reflects the law's complexity: prohibitions and AI-literacy duties applied first in early 2025, GPAI rules in August 2025, and the core high-risk obligations in August 2026, with certain embedded high-risk product rules extending to 2027. Organizations are expected to use this runway to inventory their systems, classify each by tier, and stand up the governance, documentation, and oversight machinery the Act requires. Enforcement is decentralized to national market-surveillance authorities coordinated by a new European AI Office and AI Board, and the Act layers on top of — rather than replaces — GDPR, so a single high-risk system can owe duties under both regimes simultaneously, which is why mature programs run one combined impact assessment that satisfies the FRIA and the DPIA at once.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A US company sells a resume-screening tool to EU employers. Because hiring is an Annex III high-risk use and the output is used in the Union, the company must run a conformity assessment, document data governance and human oversight, and register the system — even though it has no EU office. Extraterritorial reach makes the location of the provider irrelevant.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Memorize the tier-to-obligation mapping: <strong>unacceptable = banned, high = conformity + oversight + monitoring, limited = transparency/labeling, minimal = none</strong>. The headline penalty is <strong>EUR 35M or 7% of global turnover</strong> for prohibited uses. GPAI &quot;systemic risk&quot; triggers at 10^25 FLOPs.</div>"}
);
SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"GDPR & Privacy Compliance for AI", body:"<p>Long before the AI Act, the <span class='keyterm'>General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)</span> (Regulation (EU) 2016/679) already governed how AI may process personal data of people in the EU. Many AI privacy obligations flow from GDPR rather than AI-specific law, and the two regimes operate together. GDPR's core principles — lawfulness, fairness and transparency, purpose limitation, <span class='keyterm'>data minimisation</span>, accuracy, storage limitation, integrity/confidentiality, and accountability — apply directly to training data, prompts, embeddings, and outputs.</p><h3>Article 22 and automated decision-making</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>GDPR Article 22</span> gives data subjects the right not to be subject to a decision based <em>solely</em> on automated processing — including profiling — that produces legal or similarly significant effects, such as automated credit denial or hiring rejection. Exceptions exist (necessary for a contract, authorized by law, or with explicit consent), but even then the controller must provide safeguards: the right to obtain <span class='keyterm'>human intervention</span>, to express one's point of view, and to <span class='keyterm'>contest the decision</span>. This is why so many high-stakes AI workflows insert a genuine human-in-the-loop review — a rubber-stamp does not satisfy &quot;meaningful&quot; human involvement.</p><table><thead><tr><th>GDPR mechanism</th><th>Relevance to AI</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Lawful basis (Art. 6)</td><td>Need consent, contract, or legitimate interest to process training/inference data</td></tr><tr><td>Article 22</td><td>Limits solely-automated decisions with significant effects; requires human review and contestability</td></tr><tr><td>DPIA (Art. 35)</td><td>Mandatory for high-risk processing such as large-scale profiling</td></tr><tr><td>Data subject rights</td><td>Access, rectification, erasure, portability, objection</td></tr><tr><td>Transparency (Arts. 13-14)</td><td>Inform subjects of automated decision logic and consequences</td></tr><tr><td>Data minimisation / storage limitation</td><td>Collect only what is needed; limit retention of prompts and logs</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The DPIA</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>Data Protection Impact Assessment (DPIA)</span>, required by Article 35, is mandatory when processing is likely to result in a high risk to individuals' rights and freedoms — explicitly including systematic, large-scale profiling and certain automated decision-making, which describes most consequential AI. A DPIA documents the processing and its purposes, assesses necessity and proportionality, evaluates risks to data subjects, and identifies mitigations; if high residual risk remains, the controller must consult the supervisory authority before proceeding. The DPIA is the privacy analogue of the AI Act's FRIA and ISO 42001's AI system impact assessment, and mature programs often combine them. A worked DPIA for an AI credit-decisioning model proceeds in order: describe the processing (applicant financial and behavioral data used to score creditworthiness) and its purpose; confirm the Article 6 lawful basis (here, necessity for entering a contract); assess necessity and proportionality, asking whether less data or a simpler model would suffice; evaluate risks to data subjects (wrongful denial, discrimination via proxy features, re-identification of pseudonymized records); and document mitigations (a human-in-the-loop review satisfying Article 22, fairness testing, retention limits on prompts and logs). If high residual risk remains after mitigation, the controller must consult the supervisory authority before going live — the single step teams most often forget.</p><h3>Data subject rights and AI-specific tensions</h3><p>AI strains several rights. The <span class='keyterm'>right to erasure</span> (&quot;right to be forgotten&quot;) is difficult when personal data is baked into trained weights, prompting techniques like machine unlearning or simply excluding the data from retraining. <span class='keyterm'>Re-identification</span> risk means even anonymized data can sometimes be reversed, so pseudonymisation is treated as a control, not a cure. Models can also <em>infer</em> sensitive attributes never explicitly provided, raising fresh purpose-limitation questions.</p><h3>Lawful basis and special-category data</h3><p>Every act of processing personal data for AI needs a <span class='keyterm'>lawful basis</span> under Article 6 — typically consent, performance of a contract, or legitimate interests, the last requiring a balancing test against the individual's rights. <span class='keyterm'>Special-category data</span> under Article 9 (health, biometrics, race, religion, sexual orientation) demands a stronger condition such as explicit consent and is a frequent trap for AI teams that scrape broad datasets. <span class='keyterm'>Purpose limitation</span> bites hard on AI because data gathered for one purpose generally may not be repurposed to train an unrelated model without a fresh basis, and the GDPR's <span class='keyterm'>accountability</span> principle requires the controller to <em>demonstrate</em> compliance with documentation, not merely assert it. Cross-border training adds transfer rules: moving EU personal data to a third country needs an adequacy decision or safeguards such as Standard Contractual Clauses, which is why data residency is a recurring clause in AI vendor contracts. Enforcement gives these obligations teeth: GDPR fines reach up to EUR 20 million or 4% of global annual turnover for the most serious breaches, so a careless lawful-basis or special-category-data decision in an AI training pipeline carries financial consequences comparable to the AI Act's own penalties.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Note</div>Practical safeguards include using approved internal tools that disable data retention, redaction and filtering in the pipeline, encryption and access controls for prompts, embeddings, and logs, and impact assessments that identify personal-data categories and cross-border transfers before training begins.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><strong>Article 22</strong> is the one to memorize: it restricts <em>solely</em> automated decisions with legal/significant effect and grants the right to human intervention and to contest. The trigger word for the assessment is <strong>DPIA</strong> (Art. 35) for high-risk processing — don't confuse it with the AI Act's FRIA.</div>"}
);
SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Sector Regulation & Emerging AI Law", body:"<p>The EU AI Act and GDPR are horizontal, but much AI regulation is <strong>sectoral</strong> and predates dedicated AI law. Finance and healthcare already require rigorous model discipline, and a fast-moving patchwork of US federal guidance and state statutes adds further obligations. Compliance therefore means mapping each AI use case to the laws of its sector and jurisdiction, not relying on a single framework.</p><h3>Finance and healthcare</h3><p>In <span class='keyterm'>financial services</span>, US supervisory guidance <span class='keyterm'>SR 11-7</span> (Federal Reserve / OCC) on <span class='keyterm'>model risk management (MRM)</span> requires validation of model design, ongoing monitoring, and independent review — directly applicable to AI/ML credit and trading models. Fair-lending law (<span class='keyterm'>ECOA</span>, the Equal Credit Opportunity Act) and the <span class='keyterm'>Fair Credit Reporting Act</span> require <span class='keyterm'>adverse-action notices</span> that explain why credit was denied, which forces explainability onto lending models. In <span class='keyterm'>healthcare</span>, <span class='keyterm'>HIPAA</span> governs protected health information, and the US FDA regulates AI/ML-enabled medical devices, including a <span class='keyterm'>Predetermined Change Control Plan (PCCP)</span> approach for models that update over time.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Domain</th><th>Instrument</th><th>AI impact</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Finance</td><td>SR 11-7 model risk management</td><td>Validation, monitoring, independent review of ML models</td></tr><tr><td>Finance</td><td>ECOA / FCRA</td><td>Adverse-action explainability; anti-discrimination in lending</td></tr><tr><td>Healthcare</td><td>HIPAA</td><td>PHI privacy and security for AI training and inference</td></tr><tr><td>Healthcare</td><td>FDA SaMD / PCCP</td><td>Approval and change control for AI medical devices</td></tr><tr><td>US (cross-sector)</td><td>NIST AI RMF; EO 14110 lineage; OMB M-24-10</td><td>Voluntary framework; federal agency AI governance</td></tr><tr><td>US state</td><td>Colorado AI Act (SB 24-205); NYC Local Law 144; Illinois BIPA</td><td>High-risk AI duties; bias audits for hiring tools; biometric consent</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The US landscape</h3><p>The United States has historically favored sectoral and voluntary approaches over a single statute. The <span class='keyterm'>NIST AI RMF</span> anchors federal practice; OMB memoranda such as <span class='keyterm'>M-24-10</span> direct agencies to inventory AI and manage rights- and safety-impacting uses. At the state level, momentum is real: the <span class='keyterm'>Colorado AI Act</span> imposes duties on developers and deployers of high-risk AI to prevent algorithmic discrimination; <span class='keyterm'>NYC Local Law 144</span> requires an independent <span class='keyterm'>bias audit</span> within the prior year for any automated employment decision tool, public posting of the audit results, and at least ten business days' notice to candidates; and <span class='keyterm'>Illinois BIPA</span> requires informed written consent before collecting biometric identifiers and is enforced through a private right of action with statutory damages per violation, a frequent flashpoint for facial-recognition AI. The Colorado AI Act, the first comprehensive US state AI law, obliges developers and deployers of high-risk systems to use reasonable care against algorithmic discrimination and to disclose known risks, with the state attorney general as enforcer.</p><h3>International and soft-law instruments</h3><p>Beyond binding law, the <span class='keyterm'>OECD AI Principles</span> (2019, updated 2024) provide non-binding, values-based guidance — inclusive growth, human rights, transparency, robustness, and accountability — that anchors many national strategies and corporate codes. Common themes recur across all regimes: accountable governance, an AI inventory with risk classification, pre-launch impact assessments, lawful data use with human oversight, continuous measurement, truthful claims, third-party management, and transparency to users.</p><h3>Truthful claims and consumer protection</h3><p>A cross-cutting enforcement trend is <span class='keyterm'>AI washing</span> — overstating what an AI system can do. In the United States the Federal Trade Commission has signaled that exaggerated or unsubstantiated AI claims can be treated as deceptive practices under existing consumer-protection law, with no AI-specific statute required. The practical obligation is to align marketing copy, documentation, and user interfaces with verified results, and to keep an audit trail showing how performance and safety metrics were calculated. Securities regulators have likewise warned public companies against hype that misleads investors. The lesson for a compliance program is that ordinary, long-standing laws — consumer protection, anti-discrimination, product liability, securities disclosure — already reach AI conduct even where bespoke AI law is absent, so &quot;there is no AI law here&quot; is rarely a safe assumption.</p><h3>The patchwork challenge</h3><p>Because obligations stack — a single hiring model may simultaneously trigger the EU AI Act, GDPR, ECOA, NYC Local Law 144, and the Colorado AI Act depending on where candidates sit — organizations increasingly adopt a <span class='keyterm'>single high-water-mark control set</span> mapped to multiple regimes at once, rather than maintaining separate programs per jurisdiction. Crosswalks between NIST, ISO 42001, and the AI Act make this feasible: one impact assessment, one model registry, and one monitoring pipeline can generate evidence accepted by several authorities. This is why mapping internal policies to recognized frameworks, so audits can trace each requirement back to a concrete control, is the practical foundation of multi-jurisdiction compliance.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Note</div>Robust compliance is not purely a cost: demonstrating adherence to standards and laws can shorten procurement cycles, unlock regulated markets, and build trust with boards and regulators, while non-compliance brings legal risk, reputational harm, and lost sales.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Match the law to the sector: <strong>SR 11-7</strong> = financial model risk management; <strong>ECOA/FCRA adverse-action notice</strong> = lending explainability; <strong>HIPAA</strong> = health data; <strong>NYC Local Law 144</strong> = hiring-tool bias audits; <strong>BIPA</strong> = biometric consent. The <strong>OECD Principles</strong> are voluntary, not binding law.</div>"}
);
SECAI.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Operationalizing Compliance Across the AI Life Cycle", body:"<p>Frameworks and laws only deliver value when their requirements are embedded into the day-to-day machinery of building and running AI. <span class='keyterm'>Operationalizing compliance</span> means translating governance into automated, evidence-producing controls inside <span class='keyterm'>MLOps</span> — sometimes called <span class='keyterm'>MLSecOps</span> or <span class='keyterm'>AI TRiSM</span> (Trust, Risk, and Security Management) — so that obligations are enforced continuously rather than checked once at a launch gate. The goal is &quot;compliance by design&quot;: requirements become pipeline steps, and the pipeline produces the audit trail automatically.</p><h3>Mapping controls to lifecycle stages</h3><p>Each lifecycle stage carries its own obligations and evidence. Because AI behavior drifts, post-deployment monitoring is as important as pre-deployment testing.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Lifecycle stage</th><th>Embedded control</th><th>Evidence produced</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Use-case intake</td><td>Risk classification, impact assessment (DPIA/AISIA/FRIA)</td><td>Risk tier, approval record</td></tr><tr><td>Data preparation</td><td>Lineage capture, PII scanning, licensing review</td><td>Data provenance, consent records</td></tr><tr><td>Model development</td><td>Fairness tests, model card, experiment tracking</td><td>Metrics, documentation, version lineage</td></tr><tr><td>Validation / release</td><td>Red-teaming, sign-off gates, change control</td><td>Test reports, approval signatures</td></tr><tr><td>Deployment</td><td>Registry entry, access controls, guardrail config</td><td>Registry record, policy bindings</td></tr><tr><td>Monitoring</td><td>Drift detection, fairness re-checks, override tracking</td><td>Alerts, retraining triggers, logs</td></tr><tr><td>Incident / retirement</td><td>Playbook execution, rollback, decommission record</td><td>Incident reports, audit trail</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The model registry and continuous monitoring</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>model registry</span> is the backbone of operationalized compliance: a controlled inventory tracking every model and prompt template with its version, training-data sources, owners, approvals, and monitoring status. It makes the AI inventory that regulators demand a live artifact rather than a stale spreadsheet. Around it, <span class='keyterm'>continuous monitoring</span> compares live inputs and outputs against training baselines to detect <span class='keyterm'>drift</span>, re-runs fairness checks on real traffic, and tracks operational signals like override rates, complaint volumes, and appeal rates that may indicate harm to protected groups before metrics degrade.</p><h3>Automated evidence and gating</h3><p>Mature programs <span class='keyterm'>automate evidence collection</span> so that approvals, test results, data lineage, and monitoring status are captured by the platform rather than assembled by hand at audit time. <span class='keyterm'>Policy-as-code</span> and pipeline gates can block a deployment that lacks a completed impact assessment, a passing fairness test, or a required sign-off. Treating AI failures as operational incidents — with triage, communication templates, rollback, and corrective action — closes the loop and satisfies the post-market vigilance and incident-reporting duties that frameworks like the EU AI Act and SR 11-7 expect. Concretely, a policy-as-code rule in the deployment pipeline might assert &quot;deny promotion unless registry.impact_assessment == complete AND fairness.disparity &lt; threshold AND approvals.includes(accountable_owner)&quot;; the build simply fails closed if any clause is unmet, turning a written policy into an enforced gate that produces its own pass/fail evidence on every run.</p><h3>Roles, culture, and the audit trail</h3><p>Operationalization is as much organizational as technical. The <span class='keyterm'>AI governance engineer</span> codifies approval workflows into the pipeline; the <span class='keyterm'>MLOps engineer</span> wires drift and rollback automation; the <span class='keyterm'>AI risk analyst</span> tracks indicators such as override and error-impact rates; and the <span class='keyterm'>AI auditor</span> independently samples artifacts and logs, recreates decisions, and confirms that approvals followed policy. The aim is <span class='keyterm'>traceability</span>: from any production decision an auditor should be able to walk backward through the registry to the exact model version, its training data lineage, the tests it passed, and the human who signed off. This continuous, automated evidence trail is what lets an organization answer a regulator or a litigant promptly rather than scrambling to reconstruct history after an incident.</p><h3>From point-in-time to continuous assurance</h3><p>The deepest shift operationalization brings is moving from <span class='keyterm'>point-in-time</span> assurance — a launch review or annual audit that captures a single snapshot — to <span class='keyterm'>continuous assurance</span>, where controls run and produce evidence every time the pipeline executes. This matters because AI systems change between snapshots: weights are retrained, prompts are edited, upstream models are updated, and the data distribution drifts. A control that was true at launch can silently become false a month later. Embedding gates, monitoring, and evidence collection into MLOps means the system's compliance posture is observable at any moment, which both reduces risk and dramatically lowers the cost of demonstrating compliance when an auditor, customer, or regulator asks. This is also where AI TRiSM converges with security operations: drift alerts, override-rate spikes, and guardrail-block events feed the same monitoring and incident pipelines as conventional threats, so the AI system is governed as a living production asset rather than a project that ended at launch.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>An internal AI writing assistant for customer emails is governed end to end: the support director is the accountable owner; a system profile documents training sources and prohibited uses; pre-release tests confirm it invents no fake discounts and leaks no PII; a human agent reviews drafts until performance thresholds are met; monitoring tracks correction rates and flags spikes; and an incident playbook can disable it instantly. Every step emits evidence automatically.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>The connective tissue of lifecycle compliance is the <strong>model registry</strong> (the live AI inventory) plus <strong>continuous monitoring</strong> for drift and fairness. When a question asks how to <em>enforce</em> a policy continuously rather than document it, look for <strong>policy-as-code / automated gates</strong> in the MLOps pipeline.</div>"}
);
